# React Native Web Project

This is a **design system mobile-first app** built with React Native for Web, primarily displayed at mobile screen size.

## Stack

- **Expo SDK 55** (managed workflow) with **Expo Router** (file-based routing, root: `./src/app`)
- **React Native 0.83** + **react-native-web ~0.21** — Expo handles aliasing and bundling automatically
- **Metro** bundler for all platforms (NOT webpack) — configured in `metro.config.js`
- **NativeWind v4** + **Tailwind CSS 3** for styling — use `className` prop, NOT inline `StyleSheet.create`
- **class-variance-authority (cva)** for component variants
- **Storybook 10** via `@storybook/react-native-web-vite` for component development
- **React 19** + **TypeScript 5.9** (strict mode)

## Key Conventions

- Entry point: `expo-router/entry` (not a custom index)
- Utility function `cn()` from `@/lib/cn` (clsx + tailwind-merge) for merging class names
- UI kit components live in `src/components/ui-kit/` with barrel export in `index.ts`
- ALWAYS use `<Typography>` from `@/components/ui-kit/Typography` for text rendering. Do NOT use standard `<Text>` or legacy `<ThemedText>`.
- Each UI kit component has a colocated `.stories.tsx` file
- Theme colors defined in `tailwind.config.js` (primary, neutral, surface, content palettes)
- Legacy theme constants in `src/constants/theme.ts` (Colors, Fonts, MaxContentWidth)
- SVG icons live in `src/components/icons/` as React Native SVG components (see `svg-icon-conventions` rule)
- Hooks in `src/hooks/`, utilities in `src/lib/`

## Platform-Specific Files

Use `.web.tsx` / `.web.ts` suffix for web-specific implementations. Expo/Metro resolves them automatically:

- `animated-icon.web.tsx` / `animated-icon.tsx` (native)
- `app-tabs.web.tsx` / `app-tabs.tsx` (native)
- `use-color-scheme.web.ts` / `use-color-scheme.ts` (native)

For minor differences, use `Platform.OS === 'web'` checks instead of separate files.

## Mobile-First Layout Rules

This app is **primarily displayed at mobile screen size (~390px)**. Every screen and component MUST render correctly at narrow widths without horizontal overflow.

### Viewport & Root Constraints
- `global.css` sets `max-width: 100vw; overflow-x: hidden` on `html, body, #root` — this prevents horizontal scroll at the browser level.
- react-native-web does NOT constrain root width by default — without this CSS, content wider than the viewport causes horizontal scroll.

### ScrollView Screen Pattern (CRITICAL)
When building a full-screen scrollable page, use this pattern:

```tsx
<ScrollView
  className="flex-1 bg-primary"
  contentContainerStyle={[{ alignItems: 'center' }, platformPadding]}>
  <View style={{ maxWidth: 800, width: '100%' }} className="px-4">
    {/* content */}
  </View>
</ScrollView>
```

- **NEVER** use `flexDirection: 'row'` + `justifyContent: 'center'` on `contentContainerStyle` — this creates a row context where the child has NO intrinsic width limit and will overflow.
- **ALWAYS** use `alignItems: 'center'` (default column direction) so `width: '100%'` fills viewport and `maxWidth` actually caps it.

### Component-Level Rules
- **NEVER** use fixed-width columns or `flex-row` table layouts that exceed ~360px total — they overflow on mobile. Use vertical card/stacked layouts instead.
- **NEVER** set `min-w-[...]` or `w-[...]` on multiple siblings in a row that could exceed the viewport width.
- **ALWAYS** use `flex-wrap` when placing items in a `flex-row` if total width may exceed the container.
- **Prefer** vertical stacking for data-heavy UI (token lists, settings, detail rows). Only use horizontal row layouts for small elements like pills, badges, or icon+label pairs that naturally fit in ~160px.
- **MaxContentWidth** is `800px` — this is the outer container cap, not a safe inner width. Content must still work at `320–390px` first.

## Do NOT

- Do NOT add webpack config — Metro handles web bundling
- Do NOT use `StyleSheet.create` for new components — use NativeWind `className`
- Do NOT import from `react-native-web` directly — always import from `react-native`
- Do NOT install packages without checking Expo SDK 55 compatibility
- Do NOT create `.native.tsx` files — the default (unsuffixed) file IS the native version
